{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640211","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640211"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:13:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:13:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17812"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17812"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.86,0.02,0.09,0.02,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10526"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73215"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10526","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10526"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17812"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58686"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9891"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24570"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24994"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73215"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring normal breathing, changes in thoracic cavity volume create pressure gradients that drive air flow in and out of the lungs. This relationship becomes particularly important in conditions affecting chest wall mechanics and when managing patients on mechanical ventilation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the relationship between pressure and volume in the respiratory system?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pressure and volume are inversely proportional","Pressure and volume change independently","Pressure and volume are directly proportional","Volume remains constant as pressure changes","Pressure remains constant as volume changes"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einverse proportional relationship between pressure and volume\u003C/strong\u003E is described by Boyle\u0027s law, which states that at constant temperature, as the volume of a gas increases, its pressure decreases, and vice versa. This fundamental principle drives ventilation in the respiratory system.\u003C/p\u003E            \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E            \u003Cul\u003E                \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPressure and volume change independently\u003C/strong\u003E - These variables are inherently linked according to gas laws and cannot change independently of each other during respiration.\u003C/li\u003E                \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPressure and volume are directly proportional\u003C/strong\u003E - This suggests that pressure would increase as volume increases, which contradicts Boyle\u0027s law and would not allow for normal breathing mechanics.\u003C/li\u003E                \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVolume remains constant as pressure changes\u003C/strong\u003E - This would make breathing physiologically impossible as lung volume must change during the respiratory cycle.\u003C/li\u003E                \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPressure remains constant as volume changes\u003C/strong\u003E - This contradicts gas laws and would prevent the pressure gradients necessary for air movement.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003C/ul\u003E            \u003Cp\u003EDuring inspiration, as the thoracic cavity volume increases, intrapleural pressure decreases, creating a pressure gradient that draws air into the lungs. The opposite occurs during expiration, demonstrating this inverse relationship.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThis relationship has important clinical applications. For example, in tension pneumothorax, air enters the pleural space but cannot escape, leading to increased pressure that compresses the lung and decreases its volume. In mechanical ventilation, understanding pressure-volume relationships helps clinicians adjust ventilator settings to prevent barotrauma while ensuring adequate gas exchange.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Boyle\u0027s law states that at constant temperature, the pressure of a gas is inversely proportional to its volume.","During inspiration, the thoracic cavity volume increases, causing a decrease in intrapleural pressure that draws air into the lungs.","The pressure-volume relationship in the lungs explains how mechanical changes in thoracic cavity size drive ventilation.","Understanding pressure-volume relationships is crucial for managing mechanical ventilation and respiratory diseases."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58686"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17812"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58686"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T09:09:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T09:10:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10526"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73215"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4927"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4942"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u2699\ufe0f","name":"Physiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T12:54:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"14"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9891","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9891"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Pressure-volume relationship","synonyms":["Boyle\u0027s law"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-21T12:54:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T12:54:10